{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13158"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13158"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.03,0.7,0.12,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5595"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30767"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1995"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10351"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man is an inpatient following a pathological rib fracture sustained from rolling around in bed. This occurred in the context of costal metastases from a squamous cell carcinoma of the lung. His medical history includes moderate COPD. He does not take any regular medications. He has a 50 pack-year smoking history and drinks a can of beer most nights with dinner. His functional status has significantly declined due to his advanced cancer. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThirty minutes ago, he received an intercostal nerve block with bupivacaine for rib pain control. He is now being reviewed for acute onset restlessness and confusion. He complains of perioral numbness, dizziness, and tinnitus. On examination, he appears agitated with a pulse rate of 120/min and blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg. During the examination, he has a generalised seizure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s acute deterioration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypercalcaemia","Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy","Local anaesthetic toxicity","Hypocalcaemia","Alcohol withdrawal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Elocal anaesthetic toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient developed perioral numbness, agitation, dizziness, and tinnitus within 30 minutes of receiving an intercostal nerve block with bupivacaine. These neurologic and cardiovascular signs of excitation progressed to a generalised seizure. Local anaesthetic toxicity occurs due to sodium channel blockade, initially causing CNS excitation (restlessness, confusion, tinnitus, muscle twitches) followed by CNS depression (coma, respiratory arrest). Cardiovascular effects begin with hypertension and tachycardia, potentially progressing to hypotension, dysrhythmias, and cardiac arrest in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable consideration given the patient\u0027s advanced lung cancer, which may lead to hypercalcaemia through ectopic PTHrP secretion or osteolytic bone metastases. However, hypercalcaemia typically causes CNS depression (fatigue, confusion, coma) rather than the excitatory symptoms seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo obvious precipitant for \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypocalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E (such as osteoblastic metastases, parathyroid gland invasion, or tumour lysis syndrome) is present. Additionally, the excitatory symptoms are more consistent with local anaesthetic toxicity than hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E seizures usually occur within 12-24 hours after the last drink, while delirium tremens develops 48-72 hours after the last drink. Although the timeframe fits, the acute onset of symptoms immediately after a regional nerve block makes local anaesthetic toxicity much more likely and the patients history of one alcoholic drink per night makes this unlikely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke\u0027s encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility in this patient with chronic alcohol use. However, Wernicke\u0027s rarely presents with seizures as an early manifestation. The classic triad of confusion, ophthalmoplegia, and ataxia is seen in more advanced cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Perioral numbness, agitation, muscle twitches and dizziness may precede seizures or cardiorespiratory arrest in local anaesthetic toxicity.","Local anaesthetic toxicity is caused by sodium channel blockade, leading to CNS excitation followed by depression.","Initial management of local anaesthetic toxicity involves stopping the local anaesthetic and providing supportive care, with intralipid therapy in severe cases."],"references":["Long B, Chavez S, Gottlieb M, Montrief T, Brady WJ. Local anesthetic systemic toxicity: A narrative review for emergency clinicians. Am J Emerg Med. 2022;59:42-48. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35777259/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30767"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13158"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30767"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-22T12:47:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-22T12:47:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5595"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1106"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Seizure","synonyms":["Uncontrollable 